english:
  title: Self-Admonition
  author: Lee Gil-sang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My hair has turned half-white—am I not already old?
    Yet my daily manner remains light and childish still.
    I startle people only with nonsensical jests,
    and help the world not even with the smallest deed.
    Wine requires three cups before it quenches my thirst,
    and in all my poems, not a single line rings true.
    Heaven and earth bear such thick virtue toward me—
    so let me tend myself with care from this day forth.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is a personal reflection on aging and the gap between appearance and character, a common theme in East Asian literati poetry. The speaker acknowledges physical decline paired with spiritual immaturity, and resolves toward self-cultivation.
